The Collection hierarchy.

Java's collection framework lives in the package java util. At the top of the hierarchy is the Collection interface, parameterised with an element type E. Anything that holds elements implements Collection. From Collection branch three big families. The List interface, which is for ordered indexed sequences that allow duplicates. The Set interface, which is for groups that disallow duplicates. And the Queue interface, which is for first in first out ordered access. The Deque interface is a sub interface of Queue that allows access at both ends. Separate from Collection sits the Map interface, parameterised with a key type K and a value type V. A map associates keys with values rather than just holding elements.

Within each of these interfaces there are several implementations, each tuned for different performance trade offs. The interface tells you what you can do. The implementation tells you how fast each operation is and what the iteration order looks like. The standard practice is to declare your variable with the interface type and instantiate with the implementation type. That way you can swap implementations later without touching the calling code.
